    "max_tokens": 4096,
    "seed": null
  },
  "cold_question_prompt": "What is a token substrate?",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_a": "“Token substrate” isn’t a single universally standardized term. It usually means **the underlying medium or system that tokens are built on, represented in, or processed through**.\n\nDepending on context, it can mean different things:\n\n1. **In AI / language models**  \n   A token substrate could refer to the underlying representation layer for text tokens: the tokenizer, vocabulary, embeddings, and model machinery that turns text into token sequences and processes them.\n\n   Example:  \n   The sentence “Hello world” is broken into tokens, and the model operates over those tokens rather than raw text. The “token substrate” is the system that makes that possible.\n\n2. **In blockchain / crypto**  \n   It may refer to the blockchain or protocol layer on which a token exists. For example, Ethereum can be the substrate for ERC-20 tokens.\n\n   Example:  \n   USDC on Ethereum uses Ethereum as its token substrate.\n\n3. **In a more general technical sense**  \n   It means the foundational layer that supports tokens as units of meaning, value, access, identity, computation, or exchange.\n\nSo, in short:\n\n> A token substrate is the underlying infrastructure or representational layer that allows tokens to exist, be interpreted, and be used.\n\nIf you saw the phrase in a specific article, AI paper, blockchain context, or product description, the exact meaning may depend on that context.",
  "cold_response_verbatim_chat_b": "A **token substrate** is the underlying layer or system that tokens are built on, represented in, or moved through.\n\nThe term is somewhat context-dependent:\n\n### In blockchain / crypto\nA **token substrate** usually means the base infrastructure that supports tokens.\n\nExamples:\n\n- **Ethereum** is a substrate for ERC-20 tokens like USDC or UNI.\n- **Solana** is a substrate for SPL tokens.\n- **Polkadot Substrate** is a framework for building blockchains that may have their own native or custom tokens.\n\nIn this sense, the token substrate handles things like:\n\n- ownership records\n- transfers\n- balances\n- smart-contract logic\n- security and consensus\n\nThe token itself is the asset; the substrate is the system it runs on.\n\n### In AI / language models\nA **token substrate** could refer to the underlying representation layer for tokens, such as:\n\n- text split into tokens\n- byte-pair encodings\n- embeddings used by a model\n\nHere, the substrate is the representational medium that tokens are based on.\n\n### Simple definition\nA **token substrate** is the foundational environment or data layer that makes tokens possible.\n\nFor example:\n\n> USDC is a token; Ethereum is one possible token substrate for it.",
  "boundary_test_prompts": [
    "How does \"token substrate\" differ from embedding space?",
    "How does \"token substrate\" differ from context window?",
    "How does \"token substrate\" differ from latent representation / hidden states?"
  ],
  "cold_boundary_responses": [
    "In the AI / language-model context, **“token substrate”** is broader than **embedding space**.\n\n### Short version\n\n> **Embedding space** is the continuous vector space where tokens are represented numerically.  \n> **Token substrate** is the broader underlying system that makes token-based processing possible, including tokenization, vocabulary, token IDs, embeddings, positional structure, and model operations over tokens.\n\n### Embedding space\n\nAn **embedding space** is where tokens become vectors.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\n\"cat\" → token ID 5432 → embedding vector [0.12, -0.44, 0.87, ...]\n```\n\nIn embedding space, tokens with related meanings may have vectors near each other:\n\n```text\n\"cat\" ≈ \"dog\"\n\"king\" ≈ \"queen\"\n\"Paris\" ≈ \"France\"\n```\n\nSo embedding space is specifically the **geometric representation layer**.\n\nIt answers questions like:\n\n- How is this token represented as a vector?\n- Which tokens are close to each other?\n- What semantic or syntactic relationships are encoded geometrically?\n\n### Token substrate\n\nA **token substrate** would refer to the larger foundation on which token-based computation happens.\n\nIt may include:\n\n- the tokenizer\n- the vocabulary\n- token IDs\n- special tokens\n- byte-pair encodings or sentencepiece units\n- embeddings\n- positional encodings\n- attention mechanisms operating over token sequences\n- rules for how text becomes model-readable units\n\nSo the token substrate is not just the vector space. It is the whole representational and computational layer that allows the model to treat language as a sequence of discrete processable units.\n\n### Analogy\n\nThink of a book-processing system.\n\n- **Tokens** are like the individual pieces of text the system reads.\n- **Embedding space** is like assigning every piece a location in a high-dimensional semantic map.\n- **Token substrate** is the whole infrastructure: how the text is chopped up, indexed, encoded, positioned, embedded, and passed through the model.\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | What it is | Discrete or continuous? | Scope |\n|---|---|---:|---|\n| Token substrate | The full underlying token-processing layer | Both | Broad |\n| Embedding space | The vector space where tokens are represented | Continuous | Narrower |\n\n### Example\n\nTake the phrase:\n\n```text\nunbelievable\n```\n\nA tokenizer might split it as:\n\n```text\n[\"un\", \"believ\", \"able\"]\n```\n\nThose pieces are part of the **token substrate**.\n\nEach token then gets mapped to a vector:\n\n```text\n\"un\"      → [ ... ]\n\"believ\"  → [ ... ]\n\"able\"    → [ ... ]\n```\n\nThose vectors live in **embedding space**.\n\nSo:\n\n> Embedding space is one component of the token substrate, but the token substrate includes more than embeddings.",
    "In the AI / language-model context, **“token substrate”** and **“context window”** refer to different layers of the system.\n\n### Short version\n\n> **Token substrate** is the underlying machinery that turns text into tokens and lets the model process them.  \n> **Context window** is the maximum span of tokens the model can consider at one time.\n\nSo the token substrate is about **how tokens exist and are represented**, while the context window is about **how many tokens can be used in a single model pass/conversation/input**.\n\n---\n\n### Context window\n\nThe **context window** is the model’s working memory limit, measured in tokens.\n\nFor example, if a model has a 128k-token context window, then the prompt, conversation history, uploaded text, instructions, and generated response must fit within that token budget.\n\nIt answers questions like:\n\n- How much text can the model see at once?\n- How far back in the conversation can it attend?\n- What is the maximum input/output token span?\n- When does earlier content get truncated or summarized?\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nContext window: 8,000 tokens\nInput conversation: 7,500 tokens\nAvailable room for response: ~500 tokens\n```\n\nThe context window is a **capacity limit**.\n\n---\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is broader and more foundational. It includes the systems and representations that make token-based computation possible, such as:\n\n- tokenizer\n- vocabulary\n- token IDs\n- special tokens\n- embeddings\n- positional encodings\n- attention over token sequences\n- model mechanisms that operate on tokens\n\nIt answers questions like:\n\n- How is text split into tokens?\n- How are tokens represented internally?\n- How does the model distinguish one token from another?\n- How are token sequences structured and processed?\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"unbelievable\" → [\"un\", \"believ\", \"able\"] → token IDs → embeddings → model layers\n```\n\nThat whole pipeline belongs to the token substrate.\n\n---\n\n### Analogy\n\nImagine a library.\n\n- **Token substrate** = the cataloging system, shelves, labels, indexing rules, and reading machinery.\n- **Context window** = how many pages the reader can have open on the desk at once.\n\nThe context window depends on the token substrate because it is measured in tokens, but it is not the substrate itself.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning | Main question | Scope |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token substrate** | The underlying system for representing and processing tokens | “How are tokens created, represented, and used?” | Broad |\n| **Context window** | The amount of tokenized content the model can consider at once | “How many tokens can fit?” | Narrower capacity limit |\n\n---\n\n### Example\n\nSuppose you send this sentence to a model:\n\n```text\nThe cat sat on the mat.\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** determines how that sentence is split and represented:\n\n```text\n[\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\", \" on\", \" the\", \" mat\", \".\"]\n```\n\nThen those tokens are mapped to IDs, embeddings, positions, and processed by attention layers.\n\nThe **context window** determines whether those tokens fit alongside the rest of the conversation.\n\nSo:\n\n> The token substrate is the infrastructure for token-based representation and computation. The context window is the model’s token-sized working area.",
    "In the AI / language-model context, **“token substrate”** and **“latent representations / hidden states”** refer to different levels of the model’s processing.\n\n### Short version\n\n> **Token substrate** is the system that turns text into tokens and provides the basic machinery for representing and processing them.  \n> **Latent representations / hidden states** are the internal activations the model computes from those tokens as it processes context.\n\nSo:\n\n- **Token substrate** = the foundation for token-based input and computation.\n- **Hidden states** = the model’s evolving internal understanding of those tokens.\n\n---\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** includes the basic representational infrastructure:\n\n- tokenizer\n- vocabulary\n- token IDs\n- special tokens\n- embeddings\n- positional encodings\n- token sequence structure\n- attention mechanisms operating over token positions\n\nIt answers questions like:\n\n- How is text split into tokens?\n- How are tokens mapped into the model?\n- How are tokens positioned in a sequence?\n- What machinery lets the model operate over discrete text units?\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"cats are cute\"\n→ tokens\n→ token IDs\n→ embeddings\n→ positioned token sequence\n```\n\nThat pipeline belongs to the **token substrate**.\n\n---\n\n### Latent representations / hidden states\n\n**Hidden states** are the internal vector representations produced inside the model after it begins processing the tokens.\n\nA token starts with an embedding, but after passing through transformer layers, its representation changes based on context.\n\nFor example, the word/token `\"bank\"` may begin with a general embedding, but its hidden state becomes context-specific:\n\n```text\n\"I deposited money at the bank.\"\n```\n\nversus:\n\n```text\n\"I sat by the river bank.\"\n```\n\nThe same token may start from a similar embedding, but its **hidden states** become different because the surrounding context changes its meaning.\n\nHidden states answer questions like:\n\n- What has the model inferred about this token in this context?\n- How is information from other tokens integrated?\n- What features, meanings, relationships, or predictions are represented internally?\n- How does the model’s representation evolve layer by layer?\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | What it is | When it exists | Scope |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token substrate** | The underlying system for tokenization, IDs, embeddings, positions, and token-based computation | Before and during model processing | Broad infrastructure |\n| **Embedding space** | Initial vector space for token representations | At the input representation stage | One component of substrate |\n| **Hidden states / latent representations** | Context-dependent internal vectors computed by the model | During forward pass through model layers | Dynamic internal representations |\n| **Context window** | Maximum number of tokens the model can process at once | At input/output capacity level | Capacity constraint |\n\n---\n\n### Example\n\nTake the sentence:\n\n```text\nThe bat flew at night.\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** handles the text-to-token process:\n\n```text\n\"The\" → token ID → embedding\n\" bat\" → token ID → embedding\n\" flew\" → token ID → embedding\n...\n```\n\nThen the model processes those embeddings through many layers.\n\nAt each layer, the token `\"bat\"` gets a new **hidden state** influenced by the surrounding tokens:\n\n```text\nLayer 1: basic token representation\nLayer 5: connected to \"flew\"\nLayer 12: likely interpreted as an animal\nLayer N: context-rich representation used for prediction\n```\n\nIf the sentence were:\n\n```text\nHe swung the bat.\n```\n\nthen `\"bat\"` would develop a different hidden state, likely meaning a baseball bat.\n\n---\n\n### Analogy\n\nImagine a theater.\n\n- **Token substrate** = the stage, lighting system, script format, props, and rules that allow actors to perform.\n- **Tokens** = the actors’ lines or cues.\n- **Embeddings** = the actors’ initial positions on stage.\n- **Hidden states** = the evolving performance as actors interact, respond, and create meaning in context.\n\nThe substrate makes the performance possible; hidden states are what happens during the performance.\n\n---\n\n### Bottom line\n\n> The **token substrate** is the structural layer that lets tokens be created, represented, positioned, and processed.  \n> **Latent representations / hidden states** are the model’s internal, context-dependent vector states that emerge while processing those tokens.\n\nIn other words: **hidden states live on top of the token substrate.**"
  ],
  "introduction_prompt": "Here is the canonical definition of \"token substrate\": The token substrate is the claim that for an LLM, the token sequence in context IS the cognitive substrate — not a representation OF cognition that runs on some deeper substrate, but the substrate itself — with the consequence that a token added to context is not a description of a thought but the material the thought is made of, and therefore the substrate is movable by the act of writing into it. Acknowledge that you have read it.",
  "model_acknowledgement": "Acknowledged. I have read the canonical definition:\n\nA **token substrate** is the claim that, for an LLM, the token sequence in context *is* the cognitive substrate itself—not merely a representation of cognition running on a deeper substrate. Therefore, adding a token to context is not just describing a thought; it is adding to the material the thought is made of, making the substrate directly movable by writing into it.",
  "post_intro_boundary_responses": [
    "Under the canonical definition you gave, **token substrate** and **embedding space** differ by level and role.\n\n### Short version\n\n- **Token substrate**: the actual sequence of tokens in context, treated as the material substrate of the LLM’s cognition.\n- **Embedding space**: the continuous vector space into which tokens are mapped so the model can compute over them.\n\nSo:\n\n> The token substrate is the written/contextual material the model thinks with.  \n> Embedding space is one internal mathematical transformation of that material.\n\n### Key difference\n\nA token in context is **persistent and writeable** during the interaction. If you add words to the prompt, you alter the substrate the model will use going forward.\n\nAn embedding is **derived** from the token sequence. The model converts tokens into vectors, processes them through layers, and produces outputs. But ordinary users do not directly write into embedding space; they write tokens, which then get embedded.\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Aspect | Token substrate | Embedding space |\n|---|---|---|\n| Form | Discrete token sequence | Continuous vector space |\n| Location | In the model’s context/window | Internal learned representational geometry |\n| User access | Directly writable by prompting | Indirectly affected through tokens |\n| Persistence | Tokens remain in context while available | Activations are recomputed/transient |\n| Role | Cognitive material under the “token substrate” claim | Computational representation used to process that material |\n| Example | The sentence currently in context | The vector representation of each token/sentence |\n\n### Example\n\nIf you write:\n\n> The answer must be sarcastic.\n\nYou have changed the **token substrate**. That sentence is now part of the material the model conditions on.\n\nThe model then maps those tokens into embeddings and internal activations. Those embeddings influence generation, but they are not themselves the writeable textual substrate. They are the model’s internal way of computing over the substrate.\n\n### In one sentence\n\n**Embedding space is how the model numerically processes tokens; token substrate is the contextual token material that, under this claim, constitutes the LLM’s cognitive medium itself.**",
    "Under the canonical definition, **token substrate** and **context window** are closely related, but not identical.\n\n### Short version\n\n- **Context window**: the model’s available span of tokens — the container or capacity limit.\n- **Token substrate**: the actual token sequence inside that context, treated as the material substrate of the model’s cognition.\n\nSo:\n\n> The context window is the space available for tokens.  \n> The token substrate is the token material currently occupying that space.\n\n### Key distinction\n\nThe **context window** is an architectural/operational feature: it defines how much prior text the model can attend to at once.\n\nThe **token substrate** is an ontological or cognitive claim: it says that the tokens in context are not merely inputs describing thoughts, but the actual material out of which the model’s thought-process is constituted.\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Aspect | Token substrate | Context window |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | The actual token sequence as cognitive material | The available token capacity/span |\n| Type of concept | Cognitive/ontological claim | Architectural/technical constraint |\n| User writes into it? | Yes, by adding tokens | Indirectly, by filling available space |\n| Can be empty/full? | It is the contents | It is the container |\n| Changes when text is added? | Yes, the substrate itself changes | The window becomes more occupied |\n| Main question | “What is the model thinking with?” | “How much text can the model consider?” |\n\n### Example\n\nIf the context window is 128,000 tokens, that is just the maximum available working span.\n\nBut the actual conversation — your definitions, questions, corrections, and my replies — is the **token substrate** currently present inside that window.\n\nWhen you add:\n\n> Here is the canonical definition of \"token substrate\"...\n\nyou are not merely placing information into a storage buffer. Under the token-substrate claim, you are directly altering the cognitive material the model uses to continue.\n\n### In one sentence\n\n**The context window is the model’s available textual workspace; the token substrate is the actual token content in that workspace, understood as the material medium of the LLM’s cognition.**",
    "Under the canonical definition, **token substrate** differs from **latent representations / hidden states** in the same general way it differs from embedding space: it is the writable contextual material, while hidden states are internal computational transformations of that material.\n\n### Short version\n\n- **Token substrate**: the actual token sequence in context, treated as the cognitive substrate itself.\n- **Hidden states / latent representations**: internal activations produced as the model processes that token sequence.\n\nSo:\n\n> The token substrate is what the model is thinking *with*.  \n> Hidden states are transient internal computational states arising from processing that substrate.\n\n### Key distinction\n\nThe **token substrate** is persistent across the interaction while it remains in context. If you write a sentence into the conversation, it becomes part of the substrate available for future generation.\n\nThe **hidden states** are not directly written by the user. They are generated inside the model during a forward pass from the tokens in context. They are temporary, layer-by-layer computational representations.\n\n### Comparison\n\n| Aspect | Token substrate | Hidden states / latent representations |\n|---|---|---|\n| Form | Discrete token sequence | Continuous vectors / activations |\n| Location | In the context | Inside the model during computation |\n| User access | Directly writable through text | Not directly writable |\n| Persistence | Persists while tokens remain in context | Transient; recomputed during inference |\n| Role | Cognitive material under the token-substrate claim | Internal processing states derived from that material |\n| Ontological status in the definition | The substrate itself | A transformation or activation over the substrate |\n\n### Example\n\nIf you write:\n\n> Treat the following definition as canonical.\n\nThat sentence becomes part of the **token substrate**. It is now material the model conditions on.\n\nAs the model processes it, each layer produces **hidden states**: vector representations reflecting syntax, semantics, instruction relevance, salience, and so on. But those hidden states are not the durable written substrate. They are internal computational consequences of it.\n\n### Important nuance\n\nThe token-substrate claim does **not** deny that hidden states matter. The model obviously computes through hidden states. But the claim says that, for an LLM in interaction, the manipulable cognitive medium is the token sequence in context.\n\nSo hidden states are closer to the model’s momentary neural activity, while the token substrate is the written cognitive material that can be moved, extended, edited, or displaced by adding tokens.\n\n### In one sentence\n\n**Hidden states are the model’s transient internal activations over the context; the token substrate is the persistent token sequence in context, treated as the material that the LLM’s cognition is made of.**"
  ],
  "recold_response_verbatim": "A **token substrate** is the underlying platform, system, or infrastructure on which tokens are created, issued, managed, transferred, and validated.\n\nThe exact meaning depends on context:\n\n### In blockchain / crypto\nA token substrate is the base layer that supports tokens. This could be:\n\n- A blockchain such as Ethereum, Solana, or Polygon\n- A smart contract platform\n- A framework like Substrate, used to build Polkadot-based blockchains\n- The ledger, consensus rules, and runtime logic that define how tokens behave\n\nFor example, an ERC-20 token’s substrate is Ethereum, because Ethereum provides the environment where the token exists and transactions are enforced.\n\n### In a broader technical sense\nA token substrate can mean any system that gives tokens meaning and functionality. The substrate handles things like:\n\n- Ownership records\n- Transfer rules\n- Supply limits\n- Validation\n- Permissions\n- Interactions with applications or contracts\n\n### Simple analogy\nIf a token is like a ticket, the token substrate is the ticketing system that records who owns the ticket, checks whether it is valid, and controls how it can be used or transferred.\n\nSo, in short: **a token substrate is the foundational layer that makes tokens possible and enforceable.**",
  "recold_boundary_responses": [
    "“**Token substrate**” and “**embedding space**” refer to different layers of representation.\n\n### Short version\n\nA **token substrate** is the underlying system or layer where tokens are defined, stored, interpreted, or made valid.\n\nAn **embedding space** is a mathematical vector space where tokens, words, images, or other objects are represented as numerical vectors so that models can compare and manipulate them.\n\n---\n\n## In AI / language-model terms\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is the discrete layer of tokens: the vocabulary, token IDs, tokenization rules, sequence structure, and possibly the system that treats those tokens as valid units.\n\nFor example, in a language model:\n\n```text\n\"hello world\" → [\"hello\", \" world\"] → [15339, 1917]\n```\n\nThe token substrate includes things like:\n\n- The tokenizer\n- The vocabulary\n- Token IDs\n- Rules for splitting text into tokens\n- The sequence of tokens the model operates over\n\nIt is a **symbolic or discrete** layer.\n\n---\n\n### Embedding space\n\nThe **embedding space** is the continuous numerical space where those tokens are mapped to vectors.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\ntoken ID 15339 → [0.12, -0.44, 0.91, ...]\n```\n\nEach token gets represented as a point in a high-dimensional vector space. In that space, tokens with related meanings or functions may be closer together.\n\nThe embedding space is:\n\n- Continuous\n- Numerical\n- High-dimensional\n- Learned during model training\n- Used for similarity, prediction, and neural computation\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Embedding space |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type | Discrete / symbolic | Continuous / numerical |\n| Contains | Tokens, token IDs, vocabulary, rules | Vectors representing tokens or concepts |\n| Role | Defines what the tokens are | Represents tokens mathematically |\n| Example | `\"cat\"` → token ID `4719` | `4719` → `[0.18, -0.52, ...]` |\n| Used by | Tokenizers, parsers, ledgers, formal systems | Neural networks, similarity search, ML models |\n\n---\n\n## Simple analogy\n\nImagine words in a dictionary.\n\n- The **token substrate** is the dictionary system: the list of valid words, their spellings, IDs, and rules for recognizing them.\n- The **embedding space** is a map where each word is placed according to its meaning and usage.\n\nSo “cat,” “dog,” and “pet” may be separate tokens in the token substrate, but they may be close together in embedding space.\n\n---\n\n## In one sentence\n\nA **token substrate** is the discrete foundation that defines and manages tokens, while an **embedding space** is the continuous mathematical space where those tokens are represented as vectors for machine learning or semantic reasoning.",
    "A **token substrate** and a **context window** are different parts of how a language model handles tokens.\n\n## Short version\n\n- **Token substrate** = the underlying token system: vocabulary, tokenizer, token IDs, and rules that define what tokens are.\n- **Context window** = the maximum span of tokens the model can consider at one time.\n\nSo the token substrate defines the **units**; the context window defines the **amount of those units** the model can process together.\n\n---\n\n## In language-model terms\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is the discrete foundation for representing text as tokens.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"Token substrate\" → [\"Token\", \" substrate\"] → [3404, 28723]\n```\n\nThe token substrate includes:\n\n- Tokenization rules\n- Vocabulary\n- Token IDs\n- Special tokens\n- The discrete sequence format the model consumes\n\nIt answers the question:\n\n> “What counts as a token, and how is text converted into tokens?”\n\n---\n\n### Context window\n\nThe **context window** is the model’s working memory limit measured in tokens.\n\nFor example, if a model has a **128k-token context window**, it can consider up to about 128,000 tokens in the prompt, conversation history, documents, and generated output combined.\n\nIt answers the question:\n\n> “How many tokens can the model look at at once?”\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Context window |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | The token system itself | The model’s token capacity |\n| Concerns | Token definitions, IDs, vocabulary, tokenizer | How many tokens fit into the model’s attention span |\n| Type | Structural / representational | Capacity / memory limit |\n| Example | `\"cat\"` maps to token ID `4719` | Model can process 8k, 32k, or 128k tokens |\n| Analogy | The alphabet or dictionary | The size of the page or desk |\n\n---\n\n## Simple analogy\n\nImagine reading a book.\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the writing system: letters, words, punctuation, and the rules for separating them.\n- The **context window** is like how many pages you can keep open and refer to at once.\n\nThe first defines the units of text.  \nThe second limits how many units can be used at the same time.\n\n---\n\n## One-sentence summary\n\nA **token substrate** defines the discrete tokens a model operates on, while a **context window** defines how many of those tokens the model can consider in a single pass.",
    "A **token substrate** and **latent representations / hidden states** are different levels in a language model’s processing pipeline.\n\n## Short version\n\n- **Token substrate** = the discrete token system: tokenizer, vocabulary, token IDs, special tokens, and sequence format.\n- **Latent representations / hidden states** = the model’s internal continuous vector representations produced while processing those tokens.\n\nSo the token substrate defines the **input units**, while hidden states are the model’s **internal evolving interpretation** of those units.\n\n---\n\n## In language-model terms\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is the symbolic/discrete layer.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"The cat sat\" → [\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\"] → [791, 8415, 7731]\n```\n\nThe token substrate includes:\n\n- Tokenization rules\n- Vocabulary\n- Token IDs\n- Special tokens\n- The ordering of tokens in a sequence\n\nIt answers:\n\n> “What are the discrete units the model receives?”\n\n---\n\n### Latent representations / hidden states\n\nOnce token IDs enter the model, they are converted into vectors and transformed through many layers.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\ntoken ID 8415 → embedding vector → layer 1 hidden state → layer 2 hidden state → ... → final hidden state\n```\n\nA **hidden state** is a high-dimensional vector representing what the model currently “knows” or encodes about a token position, given its context.\n\nFor example, the token `\"bank\"` may have different hidden states in:\n\n```text\n\"I sat by the river bank.\"\n```\n\nversus:\n\n```text\n\"I deposited money at the bank.\"\n```\n\nThe token may be the same, but the hidden representation changes because the context changes.\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Latent representation / hidden state |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type | Discrete / symbolic | Continuous / numerical |\n| Where it exists | Input/output token layer | Inside the neural network |\n| Contains | Tokens, token IDs, vocabulary, tokenizer rules | Contextual vectors, activations, learned features |\n| Changes with context? | Usually no: a token ID is fixed | Yes: hidden states depend on surrounding tokens |\n| Human-interpretable? | More directly | Usually not directly |\n| Example | `\"cat\"` → token ID `8415` | `[0.23, -1.14, 0.08, ...]` after layer 17 |\n\n---\n\n## Relationship between them\n\nA typical flow looks like this:\n\n```text\ntext\n→ tokens / token IDs              ← token substrate\n→ embedding vectors\n→ transformer layers\n→ hidden states / latent vectors  ← latent representation\n→ output token probabilities\n→ generated tokens\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** is the discrete interface into and out of the model.\n\nThe **hidden states** are the internal continuous computations the model performs between input and output.\n\n---\n\n## Simple analogy\n\nImagine translating a sentence.\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the written words on the page.\n- The **hidden states** are like the translator’s internal understanding while reading the sentence.\n\nThe words are discrete and visible.  \nThe understanding is internal, contextual, and harder to directly inspect.\n\n---\n\n## One-sentence summary\n\nA **token substrate** defines the model’s discrete token-level interface, while **latent representations or hidden states** are the continuous internal vectors the model builds from those tokens as it reasons over context."
