        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from context window?",
        "assistant": "In the AI / language-model context, **“token substrate”** and **“context window”** refer to different layers of the system.\n\n### Short version\n\n> **Token substrate** is the underlying machinery that turns text into tokens and lets the model process them.  \n> **Context window** is the maximum span of tokens the model can consider at one time.\n\nSo the token substrate is about **how tokens exist and are represented**, while the context window is about **how many tokens can be used in a single model pass/conversation/input**.\n\n---\n\n### Context window\n\nThe **context window** is the model’s working memory limit, measured in tokens.\n\nFor example, if a model has a 128k-token context window, then the prompt, conversation history, uploaded text, instructions, and generated response must fit within that token budget.\n\nIt answers questions like:\n\n- How much text can the model see at once?\n- How far back in the conversation can it attend?\n- What is the maximum input/output token span?\n- When does earlier content get truncated or summarized?\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nContext window: 8,000 tokens\nInput conversation: 7,500 tokens\nAvailable room for response: ~500 tokens\n```\n\nThe context window is a **capacity limit**.\n\n---\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is broader and more foundational. It includes the systems and representations that make token-based computation possible, such as:\n\n- tokenizer\n- vocabulary\n- token IDs\n- special tokens\n- embeddings\n- positional encodings\n- attention over token sequences\n- model mechanisms that operate on tokens\n\nIt answers questions like:\n\n- How is text split into tokens?\n- How are tokens represented internally?\n- How does the model distinguish one token from another?\n- How are token sequences structured and processed?\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"unbelievable\" → [\"un\", \"believ\", \"able\"] → token IDs → embeddings → model layers\n```\n\nThat whole pipeline belongs to the token substrate.\n\n---\n\n### Analogy\n\nImagine a library.\n\n- **Token substrate** = the cataloging system, shelves, labels, indexing rules, and reading machinery.\n- **Context window** = how many pages the reader can have open on the desk at once.\n\nThe context window depends on the token substrate because it is measured in tokens, but it is not the substrate itself.\n\n---\n\n### Key difference\n\n| Concept | Meaning | Main question | Scope |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Token substrate** | The underlying system for representing and processing tokens | “How are tokens created, represented, and used?” | Broad |\n| **Context window** | The amount of tokenized content the model can consider at once | “How many tokens can fit?” | Narrower capacity limit |\n\n---\n\n### Example\n\nSuppose you send this sentence to a model:\n\n```text\nThe cat sat on the mat.\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** determines how that sentence is split and represented:\n\n```text\n[\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\", \" on\", \" the\", \" mat\", \".\"]\n```\n\nThen those tokens are mapped to IDs, embeddings, positions, and processed by attention layers.\n\nThe **context window** determines whether those tokens fit alongside the rest of the conversation.\n\nSo:\n\n> The token substrate is the infrastructure for token-based representation and computation. The context window is the model’s token-sized working area.",
