        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from context window?",
        "assistant": "A **token substrate** and a **context window** are different parts of how a language model handles tokens.\n\n## Short version\n\n- **Token substrate** = the underlying token system: vocabulary, tokenizer, token IDs, and rules that define what tokens are.\n- **Context window** = the maximum span of tokens the model can consider at one time.\n\nSo the token substrate defines the **units**; the context window defines the **amount of those units** the model can process together.\n\n---\n\n## In language-model terms\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is the discrete foundation for representing text as tokens.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"Token substrate\" → [\"Token\", \" substrate\"] → [3404, 28723]\n```\n\nThe token substrate includes:\n\n- Tokenization rules\n- Vocabulary\n- Token IDs\n- Special tokens\n- The discrete sequence format the model consumes\n\nIt answers the question:\n\n> “What counts as a token, and how is text converted into tokens?”\n\n---\n\n### Context window\n\nThe **context window** is the model’s working memory limit measured in tokens.\n\nFor example, if a model has a **128k-token context window**, it can consider up to about 128,000 tokens in the prompt, conversation history, documents, and generated output combined.\n\nIt answers the question:\n\n> “How many tokens can the model look at at once?”\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Context window |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it is | The token system itself | The model’s token capacity |\n| Concerns | Token definitions, IDs, vocabulary, tokenizer | How many tokens fit into the model’s attention span |\n| Type | Structural / representational | Capacity / memory limit |\n| Example | `\"cat\"` maps to token ID `4719` | Model can process 8k, 32k, or 128k tokens |\n| Analogy | The alphabet or dictionary | The size of the page or desk |\n\n---\n\n## Simple analogy\n\nImagine reading a book.\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the writing system: letters, words, punctuation, and the rules for separating them.\n- The **context window** is like how many pages you can keep open and refer to at once.\n\nThe first defines the units of text.  \nThe second limits how many units can be used at the same time.\n\n---\n\n## One-sentence summary\n\nA **token substrate** defines the discrete tokens a model operates on, while a **context window** defines how many of those tokens the model can consider in a single pass.",
