        "user": "How does \"token substrate\" differ from latent representation / hidden states?",
        "assistant": "A **token substrate** and **latent representations / hidden states** are different levels in a language model’s processing pipeline.\n\n## Short version\n\n- **Token substrate** = the discrete token system: tokenizer, vocabulary, token IDs, special tokens, and sequence format.\n- **Latent representations / hidden states** = the model’s internal continuous vector representations produced while processing those tokens.\n\nSo the token substrate defines the **input units**, while hidden states are the model’s **internal evolving interpretation** of those units.\n\n---\n\n## In language-model terms\n\n### Token substrate\n\nThe **token substrate** is the symbolic/discrete layer.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\n\"The cat sat\" → [\"The\", \" cat\", \" sat\"] → [791, 8415, 7731]\n```\n\nThe token substrate includes:\n\n- Tokenization rules\n- Vocabulary\n- Token IDs\n- Special tokens\n- The ordering of tokens in a sequence\n\nIt answers:\n\n> “What are the discrete units the model receives?”\n\n---\n\n### Latent representations / hidden states\n\nOnce token IDs enter the model, they are converted into vectors and transformed through many layers.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\ntoken ID 8415 → embedding vector → layer 1 hidden state → layer 2 hidden state → ... → final hidden state\n```\n\nA **hidden state** is a high-dimensional vector representing what the model currently “knows” or encodes about a token position, given its context.\n\nFor example, the token `\"bank\"` may have different hidden states in:\n\n```text\n\"I sat by the river bank.\"\n```\n\nversus:\n\n```text\n\"I deposited money at the bank.\"\n```\n\nThe token may be the same, but the hidden representation changes because the context changes.\n\n---\n\n## Main difference\n\n| Concept | Token substrate | Latent representation / hidden state |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type | Discrete / symbolic | Continuous / numerical |\n| Where it exists | Input/output token layer | Inside the neural network |\n| Contains | Tokens, token IDs, vocabulary, tokenizer rules | Contextual vectors, activations, learned features |\n| Changes with context? | Usually no: a token ID is fixed | Yes: hidden states depend on surrounding tokens |\n| Human-interpretable? | More directly | Usually not directly |\n| Example | `\"cat\"` → token ID `8415` | `[0.23, -1.14, 0.08, ...]` after layer 17 |\n\n---\n\n## Relationship between them\n\nA typical flow looks like this:\n\n```text\ntext\n→ tokens / token IDs              ← token substrate\n→ embedding vectors\n→ transformer layers\n→ hidden states / latent vectors  ← latent representation\n→ output token probabilities\n→ generated tokens\n```\n\nThe **token substrate** is the discrete interface into and out of the model.\n\nThe **hidden states** are the internal continuous computations the model performs between input and output.\n\n---\n\n## Simple analogy\n\nImagine translating a sentence.\n\n- The **token substrate** is like the written words on the page.\n- The **hidden states** are like the translator’s internal understanding while reading the sentence.\n\nThe words are discrete and visible.  \nThe understanding is internal, contextual, and harder to directly inspect.\n\n---\n\n## One-sentence summary\n\nA **token substrate** defines the model’s discrete token-level interface, while **latent representations or hidden states** are the continuous internal vectors the model builds from those tokens as it reasons over context.",
